06794nam a22008175i 9781442670310DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20161995onc    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013940559  a97814426703107 a10.3138/97814426703102doi  a(DE-B1597)464133  a(OCoLC)944178575  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aHQ1459.O6 7aSOC0280002bisacsh04a305.4/0971302aA Diversity of Women :bWomen in Ontario since 1945 /ced. by Joy Parr. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©1995  a1 online resource (335 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tContributors -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tBuilding Anti-Delinquent Communities: Morality, Gender, and Generation in the City -- tTheir Side of the Story': Women's Voices from Ontario Suburbs, 1945-60 -- tShopping for a Good Stove: A Parable about Gender, Design, and the Market -- tDoing Two Jobs: The Wage-Earning Mother, 1945-70 -- tRemaking Their Lives: Women Immigrants, Survivors, and Refugees -- tFirst-Class Workers Don't Want Second- Class Wages: The Lanark Strike in Dunnville -- tFrom Domesticity to the Public Sphere: Farm Women, 1945-86 -- tFirst Nations Women: Reclaiming Our Responsibilities -- tFeminists, Libbers, Lefties, and Radicals: The Emergence of the Women's Liberation Movement -- tMaking a Difference: The Theory and Practice of Francophone Women's Groups, 1969-82 -- tPicture Credits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOur perception of women's roles has changed dramatically since 1945. In this collection Joy Parr has brought together ten studies from a variety of disciplines examining changing ideas about women.Mariana Valverde writes about teenage girls in the immediate postwar years and finds that stereotypes of a supposedly simple, secure, politically quiescent, and sexually conformist life do not really hold. Joy Parr follows women shoppers of the early 1950s, in their sometimes comical encounters with male designers, manufacturers, and retailers, in search of the tools and totems of modernity for their homes. Increasingly these homes were in suburban subdivisions, whose pleasures and possibilities for women Veronica Strong-Boag reconsiders. Joan Sangster reminds us that wage-earning mothers were numerous in the fifties and sixties, and through a juxtaposition of their own stories with contemporary studies tells much about these self-denying women's lives. Franca Iacovetta discusses the experiences of immigrant and refugee women in northwestern and south-central Ontario, experiences that were interpreted through their starkly different European wartime memories. Based upon her work among the rural women of southwestern Ontario, Nora Cebotarev charts the changes that transformed farm families and finances from the sixties to the eighties. Ester Reiter compares the recollections of women who had worked together during the 1960s in an auto parts plant in the Niagara Peninsula with contemporary newspaper accounts of a strike, and leads us into a complex narrative of gender and militancy. Nancy Adamson reconsiders the diversity of feminist organizing within the province over the decades since second-wave feminism began; she tracks the different needs and paths that brought women to the women's liberation movement and the ways in which their feminist analysis arose from their experience as community activists. Linda Cardinal writes about Franco-Ontarian women, charting the ways in which feminist activists challenged and were challenged as they worked with traditional farm and church-based women's groups in northern and eastern Ontario. Marlene Brant Castellano and Janice Hill introduce us to four aboriginal women: Edna Manitowabi, Jeannette Corbiere Lavell, Sylvia Maracle, and Emily Faries, whose work has been to reclaim and build upon the knowledge and responsibilities long entrusted to the women of Ontario's First Nations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aWomenzOntarioxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aAdamson, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCardinal, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastellano, Marlene Brant, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCebotarev, E.A. (Nora), econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, Janice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIacovetta, Franca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParr, Joy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParr, Joy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aReiter, Ester, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSangster, Joan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStrong-Boag, Veronica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aValverde, Mariana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144267031040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442670310423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442670310.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK